@node Overview
@chapter Overview

@samp{codex.el} provides an Emacs interface to the @uref{https://github.com/openai/codex, OpenAI Codex CLI}, allowing you to interact with the Codex agent directly from within Emacs.  The package is modeled after @samp{claude-code.el} and shares a similar architecture and design philosophy.

The package embeds the Codex CLI inside an Emacs terminal emulator buffer (either @samp{eat} or @samp{vterm}), giving you a full-featured TUI experience without leaving your editor.  You can start, stop, and manage multiple Codex instances across different projects, send commands and code from any buffer, toggle the Codex window on and off, and access all of the CLI's slash commands through a transient menu.

The main capabilities of @samp{codex.el} can be grouped thematically:

@itemize
@item
@strong{Session management} --- start Codex in the current project, resume or fork previous sessions, run multiple named instances side by side, and kill instances individually or all at once.
@item
@strong{Sending commands and context} --- send freeform commands, send commands annotated with file and line context, send the active region or entire buffer, send file paths and images, and ask Codex to fix errors at point.
@item
@strong{TUI interaction} --- send return, escape, and numeric responses to the Codex TUI; queue follow-up prompts; edit previous messages; inject mid-turn instructions; open the header search overlay; and display prompt autosuggestions with a distinct face.
@item
@strong{Window and buffer management} --- toggle the Codex window, switch between instances, select from all running instances, and toggle read-only mode.
@item
@strong{Hooks and notifications} --- auto-configure the Codex CLI hooks system so that Emacs receives lifecycle events (session start, tool use, permission requests, stop); trigger desktop notifications when Codex finishes and awaits input.
@item
@strong{Transient menus} --- a main command menu and a slash commands menu, both accessible from the keyboard.
@item
@strong{Model and configuration} --- change the model, reasoning effort, sandbox mode, approval policy, and profile on the fly through transient infixes.
@end itemize

The package requires Emacs 28.1 or later, @samp{transient} 0.9.3 or later, @samp{inheritenv}, and @samp{eat}.  The default terminal backend is @samp{eat}.  You can alternatively use @samp{vterm} by installing it separately and setting @code{codex-terminal-backend} to @code{vterm}.

The development repository is on @uref{https://github.com/benthamite/codex, GitHub}.

