@node Notification functions
@section Notification functions

@findex codex-default-notification
@findex codex-display-buffer-same-window
@findex codex-display-buffer-below

The function @code{codex-default-notification} is the default notification handler.  It takes a title and message, displays them in the echo area, and pulses the mode line three times.  You can replace this by setting @code{codex-notification-function} to a custom function, for example one that uses @samp{alert.el} or the system notification center (@ref{Notifications}).

The function @code{codex-display-buffer-same-window} displays the Codex buffer in the current window using @code{display-buffer-same-window}.  It is the default value of @code{codex-display-window-fn} (@ref{Window management}).

The function @code{codex-display-buffer-below} displays the Codex buffer below the currently selected window using @code{display-buffer-below-selected}.

@node Hook handling
@section Hook handling

@findex codex-handle-hook
@findex codex-handle-hook-from-emacsclient
@findex codex-refresh-from-transcript

The hook path has two stages.  The @samp{codex-hook-wrapper} shell script is the command recorded in @samp{hooks.json}; it reads the hook JSON on standard input, writes that JSON to a private temporary file, and calls @code{codex-handle-hook-from-emacsclient} via @samp{emacsclient} targeted at the Emacs server that configured the hooks.  The wrapper retries transient @samp{emacsclient} socket failures briefly; if dispatch still fails, gatekeeping hook types such as @samp{PreToolUse} and @samp{PermissionRequest} fail closed.  The argv protocol after the hook type and buffer name is @samp{json-file JSON-FILE response-file RESPONSE-FILE ...}, so large or sensitive hook JSON does not travel through argv and Emacs can write a hook response back to the wrapper.  Hook installation also replaces older @samp{notify-emacs-hook.sh} entries so stale wrappers cannot feed hook JSON back to Codex as terminal input.

The function @code{codex-handle-hook-from-emacsclient} parses that protocol from @code{server-eval-args-left} and delegates to @code{codex-handle-hook}.  Direct Elisp callers can call @code{codex-handle-hook} with a hook type (e.g., @code{"Stop"}, @code{"PreToolUse"}), a buffer name, hook JSON data, and optional additional arguments.  It constructs a plist and runs @code{codex-event-hook} with it until the first handler returns non-nil.  Hooks marked for notification, currently @code{"Stop"}, also trigger a notification (@ref{Notifications}).

Before user hook handlers run, @code{codex-handle-hook} also updates the target buffer's transcript metadata.  On Stop events it can call @code{codex-refresh-from-transcript} internally, so a stale terminal buffer still shows the final recorded agent message.

@node Transient menus
@chapter Transient menus

@findex codex-transient
@findex codex-slash-commands

@samp{codex.el} provides two transient menus for convenient access to its commands.

The transient @code{codex-transient} is the main command menu (titled ``Codex Menu''), organized into five columns: Start/Stop Codex, Send Commands, Manage Codex, Quick Responses, and Model & Config.  The Model & Config column contains transient infixes that let you change @code{codex-model}, @code{codex-reasoning-effort}, @code{codex-sandbox-mode}, @code{codex-approval-policy}, and @code{codex-profile} on the fly without modifying your configuration.  These infixes use two-key sequences prefixed with @samp{g} (e.g. @samp{g m} for model, @samp{g e} for reasoning effort, @samp{g s} for sandbox mode, @samp{g a} for approval policy, @samp{g p} for profile).

The transient @code{codex-slash-commands} provides quick access to all Codex CLI slash commands, organized into five groups: Core (help, clear, compact, status, new, quit), Navigation & Review (diff, review, fork, resume, copy), Configuration (permissions, model, fast, plan, init, statusline, theme, debug config), Features & Tools (experimental, MCP, agent, apps, mention, ps), and Account & Identity (logout, personality, feedback).

Both transients are available from the @code{codex-command-map} keymap, bound to @samp{m} and @samp{/} respectively.

