@node Minor mode
@chapter Minor mode

@findex codex-mode

The global minor mode @code{codex-mode} enables the Codex integration.  When activated, it auto-configures the Codex CLI hooks system by ensuring that @code{config.toml} and @code{hooks.json} are set up correctly (@ref{Hooks integration}).  The mode adds a @samp{Codex} lighter to the mode line.

Activate it with:

@lisp
(codex-mode 1)
@end lisp

Or add it to your init file to enable it on startup.

@node Hooks system
@chapter Hooks system

The Codex CLI supports a hooks mechanism that notifies external programs of lifecycle events.  @samp{codex.el} takes advantage of this by shipping a @samp{bin/codex-hook-wrapper} shell script that calls @samp{emacsclient} to relay events back to the Emacs server that enabled @code{codex-mode}.

When @code{codex-enable-hooks} is non-nil and @code{codex-mode} is activated, @samp{codex.el} automatically:

@enumerate
@item
Ensures that @code{config.toml} has @code{codex_hooks = true} under the @code{[features]} section.
@item
Ensures that @code{hooks.json} has entries for all six supported hook types: @code{Stop}, @code{SessionStart}, @code{PreToolUse}, @code{PermissionRequest}, @code{PostToolUse}, and @code{UserPromptSubmit}.
@end enumerate

Each hook entry points to the @samp{codex-hook-wrapper} script, which reads JSON from stdin into a private temporary file and asks @samp{emacsclient} to pass that file to @code{codex-handle-hook}.  Existing user-defined hooks in @code{hooks.json} are preserved; @samp{codex.el} appends its own entries if they are absent and repairs them if their matcher, command, type, or timeout drifts.

You can respond to these events by adding functions to @code{codex-event-hook} (@ref{Emacs hooks}).

